image.altText: optus 'yes' sign on glass fronted office block

items.synopsis: More Australians are reporting being targeted by cyber criminals, as the nation's digital spy agency points the finger at China as the major backer of serious hacking of Australian companies and critical infrastructure.

title.children: Reports of hacking increase, China identified as major culprit

image.altText: A group of women and children on the back of a van

items.synopsis: As a humanitarian disaster unfolds in Gaza, the United States fears a power vacuum will soon follow. But Palestinian leaders say the current ideas for post-war Gaza aren't viable.

title.children: America has an idea for what post-war Gaza could look like. Here's why almost everyone is against it

image.altText: The Riverlea housing project at Buckland Park in Adelaide's north.

items.synopsis: On the one hand is a $3 billion development to accommodate thousands of families; on the other is a burial site that is of immeasurable cultural significance. The problem? They are both on the same ground.

title.children: At this housing development, Indigenous remains are being stored in a shipping container

image.altText: Israeli tanks manoeuvre near the Israeli-Gaza border.

items.synopsis: The Israeli army says it has captured several key Hamas buildings in Gaza, while those trapped inside the enclave's largest hospital say they are preparing to bury patients who have died under Israeli encirclement.

title.children: People trapped in Al-Shifa Hospital dig mass graves, Israeli minister says UN chief not fit to lead

image.altText: Glenn Maxwell and Pat Cummins walk off the field together after Australia's win over Afghanistan at the Cricket World Cup.

items.synopsis: A tropical storm currently brewing in the Bay of Bengal has the potential to interrupt Australia's semifinal at Eden Gardens, potentially gifting South Africa their first ever World Cup final appearance.

title.children: Bay of Bengal storm could end Australia's World Cup hopes

image.altText: Jim Chalmers and Katy Gallagher at a press conference on budget day

items.synopsis: What if the government kept the Stage 3 tax cuts, but reoriented them to Australians who actually need them, asks Peter Martin.

title.children: We could make most Australians richer and still save billions — it's not too late to fix the stage 3 tax cuts

image.altText: Deep learning expert and tech entrepreneur Jeremy Howard

items.synopsis: As big tech invests billions in a race to control "the most powerful technology in the world", some of AI's inventors fear the future they've helped create.

title.children: Jeremy Howard helped invent ChatGPT. As big tech scrambles for control, he fears he's failed

image.altText: An aerial shot of a sugar mill.

items.synopsis: The future of Australia's northernmost sugar mill is in doubt, sparking fears about what lies ahead for growers and the shire that relies on its economic heft.

title.children: Historical sugar mill at risk despite $45m boost from taxpayers

image.altText: A mother holds her wet newborn to her chest as they sit in a birthing pool.

items.synopsis: The ABC has heard from several women who gave birth at home after a negative hospital experience, as part of its Birth Project investigation. It comes as a Senate inquiry into birth trauma was recently launched in NSW.

title.children: Homebirths are becoming more popular, with some women choosing them after a traumatic hospital birth

image.altText: A river with a platypus bill and head just visible above the water.

items.synopsis: In response to concerns about about platypus habitat, a housing developer applying to build more than 200 homes in the City of Shellharbour has described citizen science as "unreliable".

title.children: Illawarra housing developer denies presence of platypus despite 'citizen science' and local videos

image.altText: A group of customers surround a retail worker inside of a shop

items.synopsis: Optus is no stranger to class actions after last year's cyber attack. But a week after its crippling nationwide outage left 10 million Australians in the dark and businesses unable to trade, is another one on the horizon?

title.children: Optus went offline a week ago, but it could be months before they stare down another class action

image.altText: Emma Watkins jumps in an orange dress and shoes on a pink background.

items.synopsis: The ceremony for the music industry's premier awards, the ARIAs, will take place tonight with Emma Memma nominated for Best Children's Album. So are the Wiggles.

title.children: Emma Watkins nominated for ARIA as Emma Memma in same category as The Wiggles

image.altText: A man in a grey shirt stands in front of a close carport in a driveway

items.synopsis: Victoria's Ralph Chandler watched his life savings disappear from his bank account because of a scam. He wants Australian banks to be compelled to reimburse customers.

title.children: 71yo scammed for life savings calls for refund guarantees, but bankers say it would make Australia a 'honey pot' for cyber crime

image.altText: Singer Robbie Williams poses in front of the camera at the Star casino in Sydney for the ARIA Awards.

items.synopsis: More than 30 years after Robbie Williams was a member of British boy band Take That the pop star reflects on life as a megastar in a country close to his heart.

title.children: British pop star Robbie Williams has been touring solo for 25 years and some things have changed for the international superstar

image.altText: Virat Kohli looks on while fireworks go off above him

items.synopsis: Virat Kohli has played a starring role as host nation India marched into the semifinals of the ODI World Cup. Now he hopes to carry on the legacy of his hero, Sachin Tendulkar.

title.children: Kohli carrying India's World Cup hopes on his shoulders as he looks to surpass his hero

image.altText: Parked cars line the streets of inner city Melbourne suburbs.

items.synopsis: Yarra council has voted to introduce 30km/h speed limits for almost every street in the inner-Melbourne suburbs of Fitzroy and Collingwood.

title.children: Two Melbourne suburbs to get 30kph speed limit

image.altText: Sharon Harrison kneels on the grass in her yard to show the flood damage on her property.

items.synopsis: Sharon Harrison says her property has been flooding ever since her neighbour did work on his driveway. She's spent almost three years waiting for a hearing in Victoria's civil tribunal.

title.children: Sharon says a 'creek' flows by her house every time it rains. The tribunal process to fix it is taking years

image.altText: Jordan's Foreign Minister Ayman Safadi wearing a suit speaking at a press conference with his hand raised.

items.synopsis: Jordan's Deputy Prime Minister Ayman Safadi is urging the Israeli government to cease hostilities in Gaza.

title.children: Evidence of Israeli war crimes in Gaza, says Jordan's deputy prime minister

image.altText: woman walking outside court house, wearing glasses

items.synopsis: Rachael Third, 40, has avoided jail time over her part in the theft of more than 800 cattle in Western Australia's Gascoyne region during 2020.

title.children: Woman avoids jail for cattle rustling in outback Western Australia

image.altText: A lot of silver metal pipes at a refinery at dusk.

items.synopsis: Two people have been taken to hospital after a chemical spill at an alumina refinery site south of Perth.

title.children: Two people taken to hospital after chemical spill at Alcoa's Pinjarra refinery

image.altText: Two women stand in front of a bunch of people picketing

items.synopsis: Emanuel Exports will no longer face prosecution over the deaths of more than 2,000 sheep from heat-related stress during a 2017 voyage from Fremantle to the Middle East as part of Australia's lucrative live export trade.

title.children: Dropped charges over live export deaths amounts to 'government-sanctioned torture', activists say

image.altText: A newspaper article "rag-out" superimposed over a black-and-white image of a landscape. Inset is a court sketch of a man.

items.synopsis: Stephen Neil White's crimes were so serious that a court imposed a continuing detention order on him to keep him behind bars in WA. That has now been rescinded and he will be released back into the community.

title.children: Serial rapist who attempted to murder 5-year-old girl set to be released from prison

image.altText: Andrew Giles answers a question in question time

items.synopsis: The federal government defends its security response to the release of detainees from immigration detention, insisting all are subject to strict mandatory visa conditions, with some required to report daily to border force.

title.children: Three murderers and sexual offenders among people released from immigration detention

image.altText: A selfie of a woman with red and black hair in a jagged haricut

items.synopsis: YourGround NSW invites women and gender diverse people to share their story using map locaters so public spaces can become safer and more inclusive.

title.children: A new map is letting women in NSW log where they feel safe and unsafe after dark

image.altText: A composite photo showing a hiker in the wilderness and a small Jack Russell dog in a car.

items.synopsis: Rescuers find a hiker's Jack Russell beside his body more than two months after the duo were reported missing in Colorado.

title.children: Dog found alive beside body of owner who was missing for two months

image.altText: Man standing in stripe shirt on residential street

items.synopsis: Thousands of complaints have been made about a foul stench, often compared to cat urine and rotten eggs, coming from this industrial site. Infringement notices have been issued — but not about the smell.

title.children: People want to move to this booming Queensland region. There's just one problem: despite thousands of complaints, it still stinks

image.altText: This Aboriginal woman is scared she'll die 900km away from her loved ones

items.synopsis: Robyn Nead's been forced to move hundreds of kilometres from Mount Isa to access life-saving dialysis treatment, despite it being available in her hometown.

title.children: Dialysis patient fears dying alone, far from home and loved ones, as her family members did

image.altText: Unidentified male adult walks hand in hand with child

items.synopsis: Tasmania could become the first state to introduce mandatory minimum sentences for child sex offenders after Labor flipped its position. But the controversial legislation has drawn the ire of many legal and support groups, as well as criticism from prominent victim-survivor advocate Grace Tame.

title.children: 'Great in theory but not the solution': Grace Tame slams mandatory minimum sentencing for Tasmanian child sex abusers

image.altText: Four border guards look down a dirt road as a long border fence is construced between the road and a pine forest.

items.synopsis: Finland's prime minister says the Russian Border Authority has begun allowing people to the Finnish border without required documentation.

title.children: Finland accuses Russia of trying to help asylum seekers illegally cross their border

image.altText: Nestory Irankunda of Adelaide United celebrates a goal.

items.synopsis: Adelaide United prodigy Nestory Irankunda will join German giants Bayern Munich in July next year after being sold for an undisclosed sum.

title.children: A-League transfer fee shattered as teen prodigy Irankunda signs on with Bayern Munich

image.altText: The cast of Queer Eye on the red carpet of the Creative Arts Emmy Awards.

items.synopsis: Fans of hit show Queer Eye are in shock after Bobby Berk, the show's interior design and home organisation expert, announced that the show's upcoming eighth season would be his last.

title.children: 'He's been carrying them for years': Shock as Queer Eye's Bobby Berk quits show

image.altText: Bunnings store sign

items.synopsis: Bunnings has announced it will stop selling engineered stone by the end of the year, amid calls for a total ban on the product by unions and Safe Work Australia.

title.children: 'The end of the line for engineered stone': Major retailer Bunnings to remove product from shelves

image.altText: Muhammad and Muskaan Hussain smiling in a selfie

items.synopsis: Five heart transplant patients from the same Queensland hospital contracted fungal infections of multiple strains. Two, including much-loved GP Dr Muhammad Hussain, have died.

title.children: Questions raised after five infections, two deaths among heart surgery patients from same Brisbane hospital

image.altText: Black and white composite of missing man Donald Gordon Buckley

items.synopsis: Police inquiries determined Donald Gordon Buckley had died in Moree after changing his identity, three decades after last being seen in Sydney by his loved ones.

title.children: Sydney man missing for 70 years changed his identity and died decades later, family discovers

image.altText: Volunteers go door-to-door as Category 3 Tropical Cyclone Mal tracks across Fiji

items.synopsis: The developing system is the second cyclone of the South Pacific season which only began a fortnight ago.

title.children: 'We're still coming': Tourists continue to head to Fiji as 'destructive' Tropical Cyclone Mal tracks towards Nadi
